    {
      "num": 1,
      "text": "The Beneish M-Score model primarily identifies potential financial statement fraud by analyzing which aspect of financial data?",
      "tag": "Financial Statement Fraud - Data Analytics",
      "options": [
        "B. Mathematical relationships and ratios indicating earnings manipulation",
        "A. Compliance with digit frequency distribution patterns",
        "D. Geographic patterns of revenue concentration",
        "C. Sequential gaps in transaction numbering systems"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "The Beneish M-Score uses eight financial ratios including Days Sales in Receivables Index, Gross Margin Index, and Asset Quality Index to detect earnings manipulation. An M-Score above -2.22 suggests probable manipulation. Per CFE Manual, this model identifies financial relationships indicative of revenue and earnings fraud through quantitative ratio analysis.",
      "justification_wrong": "Digit frequency distribution relates to Benford's Law, not Beneish M-Score. Sequential numbering analysis detects skipped or duplicate transactions. Geographic revenue patterns may indicate fraud but are not the basis of Beneish methodology. The M-Score specifically analyzes financial statement ratios to detect manipulation patterns.",
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "financial_transactions/quiz_001_en.json"
    },
    {
      "num": 2,
      "text": "In the Beneish M-Score model, which variable specifically measures the extent of accruals relative to total assets and is considered a primary indicator of earnings manipulation?",
      "tag": "Beneish M-Score",
      "options": [
        "B. GMI (Gross Margin Index)",
        "D. DEPI (Depreciation Index)",
        "C. LVGI (Leverage Index)",
        "A. TATA (Total Accruals to Total Assets)"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "TATA (Total Accruals to Total Assets) directly measures the proportion of accruals in the asset base and is a critical Beneish M-Score component. High TATA values indicate increased use of accrual accounting, which provides greater opportunity for earnings manipulation. The variable calculates: (Income before extraordinary items - Cash flows from operations)/Total Assets.",
      "justification_wrong": "GMI measures gross margin deterioration, LVGI assesses debt ratio changes, and DEPI evaluates depreciation rate changes. While these are valid M-Score components indicating financial stress or accounting policy changes, they do not directly measure accrual-based earnings manipulation like TATA does in the model.",
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "financial_transactions/quiz_001_en.json"
    },
    {
      "num": 3,
      "text": "Which Beneish M-Score variable specifically measures the relationship between receivables and revenues to detect potential revenue manipulation?",
      "tag": "Financial Statement Fraud - Beneish M-Score",
      "options": [
        "D. TATA (Total Accruals to Total Assets)",
        "C. GMI (Gross Margin Index)",
        "A. SGAI (Sales, General and Administrative expenses Index)",
        "B. DSRI (Days Sales in Receivables Index)"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "DSRI measures the ratio of days sales in receivables between two consecutive years. A disproportionate increase suggests potential revenue inflation or fictitious sales, as receivables grow faster than revenues. This is a primary indicator in the Beneish eight-variable model per CFE Manual 2024.",
      "justification_wrong": "SGAI measures administrative expense efficiency, GMI indicates gross margin deterioration, and TATA measures accrual quality. While all contribute to manipulation detection, only DSRI specifically analyzes the receivables-revenue relationship, which directly identifies aggressive revenue recognition practices.",
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "financial_transactions/quiz_001_en.json"
    },
    {
      "num": 4,
      "text": "According to the Beneish M-Score model for detecting earnings manipulation, which combination of index increases would MOST strongly indicate potential financial statement fraud?",
      "tag": "Financial Statement Fraud - Beneish M-Score",
      "options": [
        "D. Leverage Index (LVGI) increasing while Total Accruals to Total Assets (TATA) decreases",
